rban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Welle","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Bernhard, Math, Klaus, Otto.","North German: topographic name for someone who lived by a spring or stream, Middle Low German <i>welle</i>.","German: variant of   Well   3, in connection with this a metonymic occupational name from Middle High German, Middle Low German <i>welle</i> ‘drum, roller’, ‘rolled straw or brush bundles’, which found application in various areas of medieval life."],"variants":[{"name":"Wellmaker","meanings":["North German: occupational name for someone who manufactured drums and rollers; see   Welle   2 and   Weller   3."]},{"name":"Well","meanings":["English (London): topographic name for someone who lived near a spring or stream, from Middle English <i>well(e)</i> ‘spring, stream, well’ (Old English <i>well(a)</i>).","German: from a short form of the personal names <i>Wallo</i>, <i>Walilo</i>.","German: nickname from Middle High German <i>wël</i> ‘round’."]},{"name":"Wellmann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Helmut, Klaus, Volker.","German: variant of   Welle   1, with the addition of Middle High German <i>man</i> ‘man’, i.e. ‘man who lived by a stream’."]},{"name":"Weller","meanings":["English (Surrey, Sussex, and Kent): topographic name for someone who lived by a spring, stream, or man-made well, from Middle English <i>weller</i>, <i>willer</i>, an agent derivative of Middle English <i>welle</i> (in southern England) and <i>wille</i> (in south western England), from Old English <i>wella</i>, <i>well(e)</i>, <i>wiella</i>, <i>wielle</i>, <i>willa</i>, <i>wyll(a)</i>, <i>wylle</i>. This type of name, a topographic term + <i>-er</i>, is particularly typical of Sussex and its neigbouring counties.","English: occupational name for someone who casts metal or who boils salt, from Middle English <i>weller</i>, <i>willer</i>, a derivative with <i>-er</i> of Old English <i>wellan</i>, <i>wiellan</i> ‘to boil’. Compare 5 below.","North German: variant of   Welle  , cognate with 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":8,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705191,"age":33,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":46,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705195,"age":100,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at